{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"07057595-2813-4186-b12d-c18269ca6b93","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your crash dump. The `dump-collect` skill I have available is only for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so let me give you the key approaches directly.\n\n### Analyzing a .NET crash dump\n\n**Option 1: `dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform)\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\nUseful commands inside the REPL:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack of the current thread\n- `pe` — print the last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap overview\n- `clrthreads` — list all managed threads\n- `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` — inspect other threads\n\n**Option 2: `lldb` with SOS** (Linux)\n```bash\ndotnet-sos install\nlldb --core your-file.dmp\n# then: clrstack, pe, dso, etc.\n```\n\n**Option 3: WinDbg/Visual Studio** (Windows)\nOpen the `.dmp` in WinDbg or VS and load the SOS debugging extension.\n\n### Quick triage steps\n1. Run `pe` to check if an unhandled exception caused the crash.\n2. Run `clrthreads` to look for threads with exceptions.\n3. Run `clrstack` on the faulting thread to see where it crashed.\n\nWould you like me to help you run `dotnet-dump analyze` on your file here, or do you need help with a specific step?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5071dad9-cd50-414d-b77d-d84ecb0eddbd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\" So that skill is not appropriate here.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":476,"requestId":"7646:34F832:19BCDCF:1D5C211:69FE93E0"},"id":"d299f6ed-7a68-4bdb-8e88-ff51efef373f","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:54:52.961Z","parentId":"